---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Origins from "./_Origins.astro";
import Technique from "./_Technique.astro";
import Canon from "./_Canon.astro";
import Hidden from "./_Hidden.astro";
import Legacy from "./_Legacy.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="The Wall of Sound"
  description="How Phil Spector built a cathedral out of tape hiss and tremolo, and why its echoes still shape the music you hear today."
>
  <article id="wall-of-sound">
    <header>
      <h1>The Wall of Sound</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        A cathedral built from tape hiss, tremolo, and the sheer nerve to put
        four guitars where one would do.
      </p>
    </header>

    <aside
      class="provenance-note"
      role="note"
      aria-label="Authorship and provenance note"
    >
      <span class="provenance-label">AI-generated text</span>
      <span class="provenance-text">
        This article was drafted in conversation with an AI system (Claude, by
        Anthropic). It has not been independently fact-checked. Follow the
        links, check the sources, listen to the records. That last part is the
        real point.
      </span>
    </aside>

    <section id="intro">
      <p>
        There is a moment on the Ronettes' "Be My Baby" where the drums hit and
        the room opens up. Not a room, exactly. Something larger. A space that
        doesn't exist in any building you could walk into, a sonic architecture
        that feels both impossibly vast and strangely intimate, as though
        someone had found a way to record the inside of a feeling.
      </p>
      <p>
        That sound had a name before most people heard it. Phil Spector called
        it his Wall of Sound. The phrase stuck, the way good metaphors do,
        because it described something real: a production method so dense, so
        layered, so wilfully excessive that the individual instruments dissolved
        into a single overwhelming force. It was not a wall in the sense of a
        barrier. It was a wall in the sense of a wave.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the story of how it was built, what it did, and where it went
        after the man who named it could no longer control it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Origins />
    <Technique />
    <Canon />
    <Hidden />
    <Legacy />

    <footer>
      <p class="text-muted">
        The best way to understand the Wall of Sound is to turn the lights down,
        put on a good pair of headphones, and press play. Start with "Be My
        Baby." You will know within four bars.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>
